1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nb6 7. Ne2 c5 8. d5
O-O 9. O-O e6 10. Nbc3 Na6 11. Nf4 e5 12. Nfe2 12... Nc4 $1 13. b3 13... Nd6 {
White has a difficult game: his majority has produced a protected passed pawn,
and is thereby crippled. The blockade radiates influence. On the Queenside, he
can support the advance of his own majority, and on the other flank he puts
the requisite strength into an action by thef-pawn} 14. Be3 b6 15. Qd2 Re8 16.
f4 $1 {There are several bad points to this. It opens the diagonal of the
Black KingBishop, and introduces a danger that Black may presently get control
of e5} (16. Bh6 Bh8) (16. f3 -- 17. Rf2 -- 18. Bf1 {
Holding operation worth considering
}) 16... Nc7 17. Rf2 $2 (17. h3 17... Ba6
18. f5 18... Ncb5 $15) 17... exf4 {
Profiting from White's unprotected Queen Rook} 18. Bxf4 (18. gxf4 18... Nxe4 $1
19. Nxe4 Bxa1) 18... Ba6 (18... Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Rxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxa1 21. N2c3 $14 {
Black has weak dark squares}) 19. Re1 Qe7 20. g4 Be5 21. Bxe5 21... Qxe5 {
There are now two blockaders in action - the familiar Knight at d6 and the
Queen at e5. The stronger a piece is intrinsically, the less suitable it is as
a blockader, since the strongest piece must always flee from the attack of any
other piece. The Black Queen is in fact a poor blockader, and White should now
maneuver his piece so as to driver heraway} 22. Ng3 $2 {This is a positional
blunder, moving the Knight to a point where it is even further from attacking
the Black Queen} (22. Kh1 22... f6 23. Ng1 Nf7 24. Nf3 Qd6 25. e5 $1 25... fxe5
26. Ne4 {In view of this line, Black would had to capture the Knight before it
left e2, and this would in any case have afforded some relief to White}) 22...
Re7 23. Bf1 Bc8 24. Be2 Bd7 25. Ref1 Rf8 26. Qc1 26... Nce8 $1 {
The Knight is going to take over from the Queen as blockader at e5} 27. Kh1 f6
28. Rg1 Ng7 (28... Nf7 {more to the point}) 29. Bf3 Qg5 30. Qxg5 30... fxg5 {
White now has two connected passed pawns but neither can advance} 31. Rgf1 Nge8
32. Be2 Rxf2 33. Rxf2 Kg7 34. h3 Nf6 35. Bf3 Be8 36. Re2 Nd7 37. Rd2 37... Ne5
{The ideal position: both Knight now function as blockaders} 38. Be2 38... b5
$1 {The Black majority comes into action} 39. Rc2 Rc7 40. Nd1 c4 41. bxc4 bxc4
42. Nc3 $2 (42. Nb2 42... c3 43. Nd3 {fighting e5}) 42... Kf6 43. Nb1 Rb7 44.
Nd2 44... Ba4 $1 45. Rc1 45... Rb2 {
