preferred hypermodern, stemming from Reti; he like to play openings with
fianchettoed Bishops (Reti's Opening, etc). His positional play reminds one of
Nimzowitsch and Capablanca; and finally his defence is of the mould of
Steinitz  Petrosian build up his games along positional lines. He operated in
a straightforward manner, neither courting complications nor going out of his
way to avoid them. He also brought to his play a phenomenal endgame technique,
great tactical alertness, and patience which is nearly inexhaustiable. For
years although he certainly never avoided a contest, he hardly ever lost a
