9. Qf5 9... h5 $1 10. e4 g6 11. Qf4 e5 12. dxe5 12... Bxc5 {Now it is clear
that Black has the better of it; but in this type of play Schlecther usually
rose to the challenge with resourceful counterplay} 13. e6 $1 13... Nde5 14.
exf7+ 14... Kd7 $2 {A poor idea} (14... Kf8) 15. exd5 Nxf2 16. dxc6+ bxc6 17.
Qa4 17... Nxf7 $2 (17... Nxh1 18. -- 18... Nf2 {Which stops Rd1 later - Lasker}
) 18. Be2 Nxh1 19. Bf4 Bd6 20. Rd1 Ke7 21. Rxd6 Nxd6 22. Ne4 Rad8 23. Qd4 23...
Qa5+ {Black only chance is to counterattack and hope} 24. b4 Qf5 25. Bxd6+ (25.
Nxd6 Qb1+) 25... Rxd6 26. Qxd6+ Kf7 27. Bc4+ Kg7 28. Qd4+ Kh7 29. Qxa7+ $1 (29.
Nf6+ Kh6 30. Ng4+ 30... hxg4 $1 31. Qxh8+ 31... Kg5 {
lets Black back into the game}) 29... Kh6 30. Qe3+ g5 31. h4 Re8 32. Bd3 Kg7
33. Kd2 Qf4 34. hxg5 {White liquidates into a winning endgame} 34... Qxe3+ 35.
